Classlass,<br><br>
I have read your post with sincere interest.  I will read it many more times.  Thanks.<br><br>
I have said that I choose not to forgive and as a general position will stay with that choice.   To not forgive does not translate to hate for me.  Hate is an emotion I normally stay away from.  Did not hate the enemy.  I can hate an individual the same as I can forgive an individual.  I do not respect anyone who does not earn it.  I do not hate anyone who does earn it.<br><br>
From your post, you have gained my respect because of your honesty.  I have not walked in your shoes and did not see the carnage in the hospitals.  I can now understand that for you the only end to the suffering was to eliminate the opportunity.  Win or leave, either option would work.  You did your part and earned your place.  You supported the vet and not the war.  In many ways I believe we supported our fellow warriors by supporting the war.  The better we fought the fewer the casualties.<br><br>
We knew we could end the war quickly, but weren't allowed the opportunity.  I doubt that we could have occupied the country, but air power could have devastated it with much less risk to the ground soldier.  Our politicians made the choice.  When the war ended we (I) moved to Cambodia.  The killing was endless.  More politics.<br><br>
I was a longhaired hippie type in college.  More because the girls liked it than any other reason.  I watched the protest groups stage rallies and preach doctrine.  I stood one night and watched the physics building burn while the protestors danced in the streets.  They interfered with the firemen and students trying to fight the blaze.  Seems that science was a war tool.  That type of behavior helped me not to forgive.<br><br>
I was in Vietnam when Fonda arrived and later in the PI when she her group showed in Manila.  We threw rotten fruit at the group.  She is one I hated and still do.  No apologies.<br><br>
I did not associate with any civilian groups when I returned.  Let's say it just wasn't in my job description.  We were told to avoid civilians at all costs.  Don't talk about the war.  Since a great deal was and is classified it wasn't a problem.  After the war was over I didn't give a damn.  I had other wars and conflicts to worry about.  If someone did spit on me there would be no forgiveness, sorry.  At that time in my life I would probably have killed them.  Glad I wasn't there.<br><br>
As cook said the truth is in your words.  Your mention of Marble Mountain is a familiar ring.  Lots of action around that place.  In the time you talk about I got tangled up in a B-52 raid and almost got my butt blown up.  If you weren't there you wouldn't have known about it.<br><br>
I will read your post again and respond to other parts.<br><br>
Once again thanks.<br>

<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


